{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503205"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:56:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1943"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1943"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.07,0,0.02,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111187"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1943"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93314"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1483"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42428"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111187"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of productive cough, fever and shortness of breath. He has a medical history of hypertension, asthma and hyperlipidaemia. His medications include rosuvastatin, salbutamol and enalapril, which was commenced two weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals coarse crackles at the right base.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous blood gas:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.32 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebicarbonate 18 mmol/L (22-28)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epotassium 6.4 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esodium 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Elactate 2.6 mmol/L (0.5-2.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ehaemoglobin 125 g/L (130-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous sodium bicarbonate","Intravenous insulin with dextrose","Oral sodium bicarbonate","Urgent haemodialysis","Intravenous calcium gluconate"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hyperkalaemia in the context of community-acquired pneumonia and recent ACE inhibitor initiation. The combination of acute illness and enalapril has likely precipitated the electrolyte disturbance. The venous blood gas demonstrates a mild metabolic acidosis (pH 7.32, bicarbonate 18 mmol/L), which can worsen hyperkalaemia by promoting potassium shift from intracellular to extracellular compartments. The ECG demonstrates characteristic changes of hyperkalaemia, including peaked T waves and prolonged PR interval, indicating cardiac membrane instability and risk of life-threatening arrhythmia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous calcium gluconate\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate immediate management. It acts within minutes to stabilise the cardiac membrane by restoring the normal gradient between resting and threshold potentials, thereby reducing the risk of ventricular arrhythmias. This should be administered under continuous cardiac monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous sodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E may be given in hyperkalaemia associated with metabolic acidosis. However, it is a less effective treatment and does not provide the immediate cardiac protection required when ECG changes are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous insulin with dextrose\u003C/strong\u003E is another effective method to shift potassium intracellularly, with onset of action within 15-30 minutes. While important in the overall management of hyperkalaemia, it should not delay calcium administration when ECG changes are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral sodium bicarbonate\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this acute setting. The oral route is too slow for emergency management of hyperkalaemia with ECG changes, and absorption may be unreliable in an acutely unwell patient. Oral sodium bicarbonate is sometimes used for chronic metabolic acidosis but has no role in acute hyperkalaemia management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent haemodialysis\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive treatment for removing excess potassium from the body and may be required if medical management fails or in severe cases. However, it takes time to arrange and should not delay immediate stabilisation with calcium.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyperkalaemia with ECG changes requires immediate cardiac membrane stabilisation with intravenous calcium.","Peaked T waves and prolonged PR interval are characteristic ECG findings in hyperkalaemia.","ACE inhibitors can precipitate hyperkalaemia, particularly in patients with concurrent illness."],"references":["Depret F, Peacock WF, Liu KD, et al. Management of hyperkalemia in the acutely ill patient. Ann Intensive Care 2019; 9:32."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93314"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1943"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18785"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18785"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2f9edd98-7be3-470a-b298-7b0fa7aedbfb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2f9edd98-7be3-470a-b298-7b0fa7aedbfb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":386}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93314"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-10T13:55:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-10T13:56:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1943"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111187"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"